# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tide-rust-web
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:tide-rust-web/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:tide-rust-web/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
[src:tide-rust-web/latest-tide] Tide is a minimal and pragmatic Rust web application framework built for rapid development.
[src:tide-rust-web/latest-tide] It comes with a robust set of features that make building async web applications and APIs easier and more fun.
[src:tide-rust-web/latest-tide] In order to build a web app in Rust you need an HTTP server, and an async runtime.
